# Progress Indicators Are Required for Long-Running CLI Commands

A command that runs silently for more than 3 seconds is indistinguishable
from a frozen program. This is a usability defect, not a cosmetic preference.

## The rule

Any CLI operation with an expected runtime over 3 seconds must provide
one of the following:

- A `click.progressbar` with a tick per unit of work (preferred when total
  count is known before the work begins).
- A per-item echo line with a running counter (when total count is unknown
  until the work is done).
- A spinner or "working..." echo followed by periodic status lines (for
  operations that cannot be decomposed into discrete units).

## What counts as "over 3 seconds"

- Any operation that makes more than one HTTP request.
- Any operation that reads or writes more than a few hundred database rows.
- Any file system operation that processes more than a handful of files.
- Any operation whose runtime scales with user data and is unbounded.

## What is not required

- Operations that are always fast regardless of data volume (e.g. `status`
  reading a single aggregate query).
- Operations where the total time is always under 1 second.

## Prohibited

- A command that emits "Starting..." and then goes silent until completion.
- A command that only reports results after all work is done, with no
  intermediate feedback, when the work takes more than 3 seconds.

